## Type of Change: bug

API not changed.

## Description
Force CMake to add `--std=c11` / `--std=c++11` to avoid unexpected optimization which may affect the precision of floating point accuracy.

Previously, we only specify `target_compile_features(${TARGET} PUBLIC c_std_11 / cxx_std_11)`. However, [if the compiler's default standard level is at least that of the requested feature, CMake may omit the `-std=` flag](https://cmake.org/cmake/help/latest/manual/cmake-compile-features.7.html#compile-feature-requirements). Therefore, I suggest adding `<LANG>_STANDARD` and `<LANG>_STANDARD_REQUIRED` to make sure that the flag is allways added. In addition, `<LANG>_EXTENSIONS` are turned off so that the generated flags will be something like `--std=c11` rather than `--std=gunc11`.

The point to add languages flags is that compilers will apply non-standard optimizations otherwise. For example, [`-ffp-contract` is turned to `fast` when no language standard specified](https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Optimize-Options.html#index-ffp-contract) which will fuse multiply and addition together, introducing numerical errors. It also causes unaligned behaviors between Debug and Release builds which make it harder to differentiate causes of errors during debugging.

<details>
<summary>Ref: A trivial test program</summary>

```
#include <math.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main(int argc, char const* argv[]) {
  float theta = 0x1.7ff222p-1;
  // 7.317610e-01,0x1.76a96p-1 6.815614e-01,0x1.5cf59cp-1 5.623413e-01,0x1.1feb34p-1
  const float cos_theta = cosf(theta);
  const float sin_theta = sinf(theta);
  // printf("%+a %+a %+a\n", cos_theta, sin_theta, theta);

  // -1.584280e+00,-0x1.95935ap+0 1.000486e+00,0x1.001fe2p+0
  float x0 = -0x1.95935ap+0;
  float x1 = 0x1.001fe2p+0;
  // printf("%+a %+a\n", x0, x1);
  int tmp;
  scanf("%d", &tmp);

  float d0 = tmp * x0 * cos_theta - x1 * sin_theta;
  float d1 = tmp * x0 * sin_theta + x1 * cos_theta;
  printf("%f %f; %+a %+a\n", d0, d1, d0, d1);

  return 0;
}
```

Run with
- `gcc -O0 -mfma -lm ./test.c -o test && echo 1 | ./test`
  > -1.841207 -0.347667; -0x1.d75958p+0 -0x1.6402c4p-2
- `gcc -O3 -mfma -lm ./test.c -o test && echo 1 | ./test`
  > -1.841207 -0.347667; -0x1.d75956p+0 -0x1.6402c4p-2
- `gcc -O3 --std=c11 -mfma -lm ./test.c -o test && echo 1 | ./test`
  > -1.841207 -0.347667; -0x1.d75958p+0 -0x1.6402c4p-2
</details>

## Expected Behavior & Potential Risk
Adding language standard specification will disable some non-standard optimizations and thus affects performance. However, it should not have too much overhead as 1) most of C/C++ implemented layers are memory-bound; 2) compute bound layers like inner product are implemented using JIT via jblas.

